{"timestamp": "2025-12-03 12:39:51.578030", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Diagnostic Report — Clos Fabric (EBGP) — Current State\n\nExecutive summary\n- Overall fabric health: BGP sessions between super-spine, spines and leaves are up and exchanging routes; multi-path nexthops and prefix counts look consistent across routers. Most host-to-host reachability checks succeeded.\n- Anomaly: Only host pc_0_0 (10.0.0.2) shows failed/unknown reachability in the automated tests. All other hosts tested can reach each other.\n- Localization: Problem is localized to leaf_router_0_0 (the leaf that serves 10.0.0.0/24) and the attached host pc_0_0.\n- Root cause (most likely): leaf_router_0_0 has a kernel route entry for 10.0.0.0/24 configured as a blackhole instead of a connected route via its interface. That blackhole will cause traffic to/from the 10.0.0.0/24 subnet to be dropped locally on the leaf, explaining pc_0_0’s lack of reachability while the rest of the BGP fabric remains healthy.\n\nKey evidence and observations\n\n1) Reachability scan (summary)\n- The reachability tool returned many successful ping results between pods/pods’ hosts (status \"ok\" with 0% loss).\n- Only entries with problems: probes with src = pc_0_0 to other hosts had status \"unknown\" (the rest of hosts tested returned \"ok\"). This indicates a host- or leaf-specific problem rather than widespread routing failure.\n\n2) Host (pc_0_0) local config\n- pc_0_0:\n  - eth0: 10.0.0.2/24 (UP)\n  - Default route: via 10.0.0.1\n  - RX/TX counters show interface is up and transmitting.\n- This indicates the host IP configuration and default gateway are present and the L1/L2 interface appears up.\n\n3) Leaf router (leaf_router_0_0) interface and route state\n- Interfaces:\n  - eth8: 10.0.0.1/24 present on leaf_router_0_0 (interface exists and is UP).\n- Routing table (important line):\n  - leaf_router_0_0 ip_route shows: \"blackhole 10.0.0.0/24\"\n  - It also shows many BGP-learned routes and nexthops for other prefixes.\n- Contrast: leaf_router_0_1 (serving 10.0.1.0/24) shows the expected connected route:\n  - leaf_router_0_1 ip_route: \"10.0.1.0/24 dev eth8 proto kernel scope link src 10.0.1.1\"\n\nImplication: leaf_router_0_0 has a blackhole route for its own host subnet (10.0.0.0/24) even though the interface has the IP. That blackhole route will cause packets destined for 10.0.0.0/24 to be dropped on the leaf rather than forwarded to the directly-connected host.\n\n4) BGP state\n- leaf_router_0_0 BGP summary:\n  - All configured EBGP neighbors (spines) are up; PfxRcd/PfxSnt values show prefixes are exchanged (Neighbors 8, PfxSnt=32).\n- spine and super-spine summaries:\n  - spine_router_0_0 and spine_router_0_1 sessions to super-spine are up and to leaves are up; prefix counts consistent.\n- Conclusion: BGP control-plane is healthy and prefix distribution across the fabric is functioning. The issue is not due to BGP neighbor down or missing prefix advertisement.\n\nWhy this explains the observed symptom\n- The BGP control-plane and fabric forwarding toward the leaf are fine (spine entries show next-hop to 10.0.0.0/24 via leaf_router_0_0).\n- However, because the leaf has a blackhole route for 10.0.0.0/24, the leaf will not forward traffic to the host; local traffic will be discarded (or sinkholed). That results in pc_0_0 appearing unreachable to the rest of the network while all other hosts remain reachable.\n\nLocalization summary\n- Faulty device(s): leaf_router_0_0 (primary), and impacted host pc_0_0 (symptom).\n- Fabric components verified healthy: spine_router_0_0, spine_router_0_1, super_spine_router_0 — BGP and routing appear consistent and peers are established across the fabric.\n\nRoot-cause analysis (most likely)\n- A blackhole route exists on leaf_router_0_0 for 10.0.0.0/24 while the interface has 10.0.0.1/24 configured.\n- Potential cause(s) (observational — not prescriptive):\n  - FRR/route management on leaf_router_0_0 inserted/installed a blackhole route for the prefix instead of / in addition to or replacing the kernel connected route (possible interaction between FRR’s network statement and route installation).\n  - Race or misconfiguration at the leaf when the network was configured in FRR (or the kernel route was not present when FRR added network, leading FRR to create a blackhole route).\n  - Local routing table inconsistency on leaf_router_0_0 causing connected route to be masked by a higher-priority blackhole entry.\n- Note: Control-plane (BGP) is announcing the prefix and neighbors are exchanging prefixes — the blackhole is local dataplane/kernel-level behavior.\n\nAdditional notes / evidence excerpts\n- leaf_router_0_0 ip_route excerpt: shows \"blackhole 10.0.0.0/24\".\n- leaf_router_0_0 ifconfig: eth8 has inet 10.0.0.1/24 (interface is present and up).\n- leaf_router_0_0 BGP summary: peers up, PfxSnt = 32, PfxRcd = 31 (normal).\n- leaf_router_0_1 (neighboring leaf) shows proper connected route for 10.0.1.0/24 and similar BGP state — supports that the issue is specific to leaf_router_0_0.\n\nImpact and severity\n- Scope: Single host subnet (10.0.0.0/24) — pc_0_0 unable to reach/ be reached by the rest of the fabric. All other subnets/hosts appear functional.\n- Severity: Medium for service(s)/users relying on pc_0_0; low for overall fabric stability (control-plane healthy).\n\nConclusion\n- The fabric's BGP control-plane is healthy and working. The operational impact is localized to leaf_router_0_0 because of a blackhole route for 10.0.0.0/24 in the leaf's routing table despite the interface having the correct IP. This blackhole is the most direct explanation for pc_0_0’s reachability failures.\n\nIf you want, I can run targeted commands next (examples: show ip route on leaf_router_0_0 in more detail, show kernel route entries, or ping/traceroute from leaf_router_0_0 to pc_0_0 and from other routers toward 10.0.0.2) to collect additional evidence for deeper root-cause confirmation. (No remediation provided unless you request it.)", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 45378, "output_tokens": 3227, "total_tokens": 48605, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 44672}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1664}}}
